  "prompt": "What subtle signs did you first notice when your antidepressant started working?",
  "response": "When an antidepressant starts working, the changes can be subtle and may vary from person to person. Here are some signs that people commonly report:\n\n1. **Improved Mood Stability**: You might notice that your mood doesn't swing as drastically as before. Small setbacks or challenges might not throw you off as much.\n\n2. **Increased Energy**: You may feel less fatigued and more motivated to engage in daily activities. This might manifest as having the energy to do things you previously found exhausting.\n\n3. **Better Sleep**: If you were experiencing insomnia or disrupted sleep, you might find it easier to fall asleep and stay asleep, or you might feel more rested upon waking.\n\n4. **More Interest in Activities**: You may start to enjoy activities that you had lost interest in. This can be a sign that your anhedonia (loss of pleasure) is lifting.\n\n5. **Reduced Anxiety**: If you were experiencing anxiety alongside depression, you might notice a decrease in anxious thoughts or physical symptoms of anxiety.\n\n6. **Clearer Thinking**: You might find it easier to concentrate and make decisions. The mental fog that often accompanies depression might start to lift.\n\n7. **Increased Social Interaction**: You may feel more inclined to reach out to friends and family, or to engage in social activities that you had been avoiding.\n\n8. **Improved Appetite**: If your depression affected your eating habits, you might notice your appetite returning to normal.\n\nThese changes might not be dramatic at first, and it's important to give the medication enough time to take full effect, which can sometimes take several weeks. It's also crucial to communicate with your healthcare provider about any changes you experience, positive or negative, to ensure the treatment plan is working effectively for you.",
